transcription.text:
Speaker 1: Thank you for calling. This is John. How can I help you?

Speaker 2: Yeah, I'm calling about a tracking number. I've been tracking a package and it seems like it came and went.

Speaker 1: It's going back again. It didn't get delivered twice.

Speaker 2: Can I get your name and zip code?

Speaker 1: Yeah, Eugene Cooper 32940.

Speaker 2: So I see what you're talking about, sir. I'm not exactly sure. I'm not the post office.

Speaker 1: What I would suggest is you call the post office with that tracking number.

Speaker 2: And ask them why it went back to North Carolina after it was just in Florida.

Speaker 1: That would be your best bet.

Speaker 2: If they tell you something like we were returning it or it got lost or something, we'll just reship it to you.

Speaker 1: But I would check with them first because I don't have a reason for why it's doing that.

Speaker 2: But I see what you're saying, too.

Speaker 1: Yeah, okay. It never was delivered. I don't know. It's kind of weird.

Speaker 2: You've got to call the post office because I don't work for them.

Speaker 1: So give them that tracking number. They'll have more information on what's going on with that package.

Speaker 2: If they tell you it's lost or it's not going to arrive...

Speaker 1: Do I have to go there or I can call? Is there a number to call?

Speaker 2: It's super easy, sir. You just look up your local post office number.

Speaker 1: And give them that tracking number that you already have. That's all you have to do.

Speaker 2: Okay, thank you.

Speaker 1: Welcome.

Speaker 2: Bye.
